longTermOutlook.stateDescription: Recent bullish events outweigh bearish events.

msBullishSummary: According to Euromonitor, Old Navy was the second-largest apparel brand (after Nike) in the U.S. in 2022. It competes in the discount apparel sector, which has been healthier than other areas of apparel retail.
Athleta has established itself in the fast-growing women’s athleisure market, one of the bright spots in North America apparel. Its merchandize carries higher price points than other Gap brands.
Gap’s e-commerce accounted for $5 billion in sales in 2022 (32% of its total sales) and has helped the firm to become less dependent on indoor malls.
msBearishSummary: Gap’s poor results and significant management turnover make it highly unlikely that the company will achieve its stated targets, such as a 10% operating margin, in the foreseeable future.

We believe Old Navy generates most of Gap’s operating profit, but its same-store sales have been inconsistent due, in part, to merchandising issues. The ultimate success of Gap’s turnaround plan for the brand is uncertain.
Banana Republic and Gap Global continue to post disappointing results, suggesting that closing low-performing stores has brought little benefit.

researchReports.title: Gap Earnings: Nice Start to New CEO’s Tenure as Old Navy and Margins Outperform; Shares Undervalued
researchReports.summary: Gap retails apparel, accessories, and personal-care products under the Gap, Old Navy, Banana Republic, and Athleta brands. Old Navy generates more than half of Gap’s sales. The firm also operates e-commerce sites, outlet stores, and specialty stores under various Gap names. Gap operates approximately 2,600 stores in North America, Europe, and Asia and franchises about 850 more in Asia, Europe, Latin America, and other regions. Gap was founded in 1969 and is based in San Francisco.
